		<img width="2500" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-barn-owls-houses-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">In British Columbia, barn owls fledge in mid-summer, much later in the year than owls farther south. The regional adaptation meant many juvenile birds were still too young to fly when a deadly heat dome cooked the province in June 2021. Photo by John Gordon</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Climate Change and Housing Adaptation: Owl Edition</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">After scores of barn owls died in overheated nest boxes, conservationists set out to give the birds less heat-prone homes.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/larry-pynn/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Larry Pynn</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						May 15, 2024 | 800 words, about 4 minutes
					</aside>

					
